1.description:
&lt;p&gt;Internationalization, or i18n, is the process of developing your plugin or theme so it can easily be translated into other languages. And since WordPress is used all over the world, it&#x27;s important to ensure your code can be easily translated into whatever language is needed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this final unit in this Intermediate course, you&#x27;ll learn how to get your code translation-ready for users, in other words, how to &lt;em&gt;internationalize&lt;/em&gt; it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You&#x27;ll do three things:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Learn about internationalization and what it is.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Get your code ready for translation with some WordPress functions.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Create a text domain, which WordPress uses to translate your code.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You&#x27;ll need to have a theme and/or plugins to work with if you want to work along – either continue with the code you&#x27;ve developed during the series or download it from the &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/rachelmccollin/wpmudev-intermediate-WordPress-development&quot;&gt;source files&lt;/a&gt;. You&#x27;ll also need the code from the previous unit in this course, Working with Metadata.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let&#x27;s start with an overview of translation and internationalization.&lt;/p&gt;

